introduction.p:
When a set does not contain too many elements it is fine to specify it by listing out its  elements.  But for infinite sets or even just big sets we can't do this and instead we  have to give the defining rule. For example the set of all perfect square numbers we write as


  S &= \{x \st x = k^2 \mbox{ where } k \in \mathbb{Z} \}


Notice we have used another piece of short-hand here, namely \st, which stands for such that or so that. We read the above statement as S is the set of elements x such that x equals k-squared where k is an integer. This is the standard way of writing a set defined by a rule, though there are  several shorthands for such that. We shall use two them:


  P &= \{ p \st p \mbox{ is prime} \} = \{ p \,|\, p \mbox{ is prime} \}


Other people also use : is shorthand for such that. You should recognise all  three of these shorthands.

statement.p:
We also define half-open

	Also called half-closed. The  preference for one term over the other may be related to whether a 500ml glass containing 250ml of water is half-full or half-empty.

intervals which contain one end point but not the other:


  (a,b] &= \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : a  \lt  x \leq b\}
  & [a,b) &= \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : a \leq x  \lt  b\}


We sometimes also need unbounded intervals


  [a, \infty) &= \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : a \leq x \}
  & (a, \infty) &= \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : a  \lt  x \}

  (\infty, b] &= \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : x \leq b \}
  & (\infty, b) &= \{ x \in \mathbb{R} : x  \lt  b \}


These unbounded intervals do not include \infty, so that end of the interval is always open

	Infinity is not a real number. As mentioned in an earlier footnote, Cantor proved that there are an infinite number of different infinities and so it is incorrect to think of \infty as being a single number. As such it cannot be an element in an interval of the real line. We suggest that the reader that wants to learn  more about how mathematics handles infinity look up transfinite numbers and  transfinite arithmetic. Needless to say these topics are beyond the scope of this text.
	.

example.p:
Let A = \{1,2,3,4 \}, B = \{p : p \mbox{ is prime} \}, C = \{5,7,9\} and D = \{\mbox{even positive integers}\}. Then


  A \cap B &= \{2,3\}

  B \cap D &= \{2 \}

  A \cup C &= \{1,2,3,4,5,7,9\}

  A \cap C &= \es


In this last case we see that the two sets have no elements in common  they are said to bedisjoint.
